	<clause id="_experience" obligation="normative"><title>Experience</title><clause id="_background_the_bulk_value_of_si_unit_cell_d_220" obligation="normative">
	<title>Background — the bulk value of Si unit cell <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>220</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem></title>
	<p id="_6b7fcb9a-4422-4cb2-b03c-aa0963fc7d7b">The lattice constant of silicon has been determined on bulk silicon crystals with very small uncertainty down to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mrow></msup></math></stem> or less by using optical interferometry combined with x-ray interferometry <eref type="inline" bibitemid="andreas" citeas="[3]"/>. Up to now all of the measurements performed are in good agreement <eref type="inline" bibitemid="mohr" citeas="[4]"/>. For measurement in the nanometre region alone, the Si lattice spacing can be regarded as a natural constant <eref type="inline" bibitemid="andreas" citeas="[3]"/> with a known uncertainty.</p>
	</clause>
	<clause id="_crystalline_surfaces_under_uhv_conditions" obligation="normative"><title>Crystalline surfaces under UHV conditions</title><p id="_f2e52d16-d91f-41a1-9587-15bb733f93b0">Clean crystalline surfaces, <em>i.e.</em> free of oxygen and other contamination,
